This French-language blog post from Kompozite discusses the CO2 equivalent (CO2e), a critical unit of measurement for greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. The article explains the importance of this standardized measurement in understanding and quantifying the global warming potential of different greenhouse gases. CO2 equivalent helps scientists, policymakers, and organizations compare and assess the climate impact of various gases by converting them to a common scale based on their warming potential relative to carbon dioxide. This method allows for more accurate tracking and comparison of emissions across different sectors and sources, supporting more effective climate change mitigation strategies and environmental reporting.
